{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487275"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"306"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/306"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.1,0.43,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52664"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/306"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38027"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1811"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52664"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of sudden onset skin eruptions. He is febrile and is commenced on intravenous flucloxacillin and vancomycin for an infected cardiac pacemaker. On examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 38.5\u00b0C. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, and respiratory rate 18/min. Skin examination reveals well-defined tender pustules and nodules across his body (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/17d140b9-4884-4daf-9b92-75e61a709903.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 1\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/1892322b-2fdd-42c4-ae34-be5099f15fd7.jpg\u0022\u003E2\u003C/a\u003E). A skin biopsy is performed, which shows a diffuse neutrophilic infiltrate in the reticular dermis.  The infected pacemaker is removed and cultured; it grows \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sweet syndrome","Pyoderma gangrenosum","Erythema multiforme","Erythema elevatum diutinum","Beh\u00e7et disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003ESweet syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as acute febrile neutrophilic dermatosis. It is a rare, non-infectious, non-vasculitic disorder characterized by neutrophilic skin infiltration. It typically presents with sudden onset of well-defined tender plaques or nodules accompanied by fever, arthralgias, ocular inflammation, headaches, and, rarely, oral or genital lesions.  Whilst not a common disorder, it is important to recognise the characteristic appearances. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESweet syndrome may be idiopathic or associated with an underlying condition, such as malignancy and some inflammatory and autoimmune diseases. In other presentations, post-infectious and drug-induced Sweet syndrome have been described. Sweet syndrome in drug-induced cases occurs after exposure and re-exposure to the responsible drug and resolves with or without corticosteroids after the withdrawal of the drug. In this case, the pacemaker infection or subsequent treatment with antibiotics may have precipitated the development of Sweet syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon drug triggers for Sweet syndrome include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG-CSF\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral antibiotics (minocycline, nitrofurantoin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, norfloxacin, ofloxacin)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntihypertensives (hydralazine, furosemide), NSAIDs (diclofenac, celecoxib), immunosuppressives (azathioprine)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiepileptics (carbamazepine, diazepam)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-cancer (bortezomib, imatinib mesylate, ipilimumab, lenalidomide, topotecan, vemurafenib)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntipsychotics (clozapine)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntithyroid (propylthiouracil)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis is based on the presence of major and minor criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor criteria\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eabrupt onset of typical cutaneous lesions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehistopathology consistent with Sweet syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinor criteria\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elesions preceded by one of the associated infections or vaccinations; accompanied by one of the associated malignancies or inflammatory disorders; associated with drug exposure or pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epresence of fever and constitutional signs and symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eleukocytosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eexcellent response to systemic corticosteroids\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth the major and any two of the minor criteria are required for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyoderma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E is also another neutrophilic dermatosis. It is an uncommon, ulcerative cutaneous condition. Classic pyoderma gangrenosum is characterized by deep ulceration with a violaceous border that overhangs the ulcer bed. Histologically, pyoderma gangrenosum and Sweet syndrome are indistinguishable but can be differentiated based on presentation and the physical appearance of the lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute, self-limited condition considered a type IV hypersensitivity reaction associated with certain infections, medications, and various other triggers. The hallmark of erythema multiforme is a target lesion. Histologically it is characterized by lymphocytic infiltrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema elevatum diutinum\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare, chronic dermatosis. It is characterized by red\u2013violet to red\u2013brown papules, plaques, and nodules that favour extensor surfaces. It is a benign skin condition which can occur in association with infections, haematologic abnormalities, autoimmune diseases, or other conditions. Histologically, it is characterized by early changes of a leukocytoclastic vasculitis with a polymorphonuclear cell infiltrate and deposition of fibrin in the superficial and mid dermis, which is not the case in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeh\u00e7et disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a multi-system inflammatory disease characterised by recurrent oral-genital ulcers, uveitis, skin lesions and pathergy. Histological findings are variable and dependent upon the type of lesion. Pathergic lesions are characterised by a heavy neutrophilic infiltrate without fibrin within the vessel walls. The presentation in this scenario is not suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EBeh\u00e7et disease\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sweet syndrome is febrile neutrophilic dermatosis which is a non-infectious disorder of the skin","Histologically it is characterized by neutrophilic infiltration of the dermis"],"references":["Vashisht P, Goyal A, Hearth Holmes MP. Sweet Syndrome. [Updated 2022 Sep 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431050/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38027"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"306"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18836"},{"type":"media","id":"18837"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18836"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17d140b9-4884-4daf-9b92-75e61a709903.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17d140b9-4884-4daf-9b92-75e61a709903.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":349}},{"type":"media","id":"18837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18837"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1892322b-2fdd-42c4-ae34-be5099f15fd7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1892322b-2fdd-42c4-ae34-be5099f15fd7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":409}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38027"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-08T21:58:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T21:59:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"306"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52664"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"